============================================================================

                      T F   C D 3 2   R I S E R
                     USB Input - Read Me / Guide

============================================================================

  Use modern USB gamepads, keyboards and mice on your Amiga / CD32.
  This file explains how the USB feature works, what hardware is
  compatible, how to choose a gamepad, and how to use the "risergamepad"
  configuration tool.

  Updated: 26-May-2026


----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1.  WHAT THE RISER DOES
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  The riser carries a small USB host (an STM32 microcontroller).  It reads
  ordinary USB input devices and feeds the Amiga exactly the signals it
  already understands:

    *  a USB gamepad / joystick  ->  the Amiga joystick (and CD32) port
    *  a USB mouse               ->  the Amiga mouse port
    *  a USB keyboard            ->  the Amiga keyboard

  To the Amiga it all looks like the genuine article.  There is NO driver
  to install and nothing to run at boot: it works in Workbench, in the
  early boot menu, and in games that bang the hardware directly, because
  the riser presents real joystick / mouse / keyboard signals.

  The riser has TWO USB ports.  How devices are assigned:

    *  One gamepad            ->  joystick port  (the port marked "1"
                                   on a CD32)
    *  A second gamepad       ->  mouse port      (the port marked "2")
    *  A USB mouse            ->  mouse port  (a mouse always wins the
                                   mouse port over a 2nd gamepad)
    *  A USB keyboard         ->  acts as the Amiga keyboard

  A single mapped gamepad can act as BOTH a normal Amiga joystick (up /
  down / left / right + fire) AND a full 7-button CD32 controller (the
  Red / Blue / Green / Yellow buttons plus Play and the two shoulder
  buttons).  Games get whichever they ask for.


----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  2.  PER-GAMEPAD PROFILES
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Every gamepad reports a USB identity (its "VID:PID").  The riser stores
  a button mapping for each pad keyed to that identity:

    *  Map your pad once (see section 5).
    *  Unplug it, plug it back in - into EITHER port - and its mapping
       loads automatically.
    *  Up to 4 different gamepads are remembered, even after power-off.

  So you can keep several pads and each just works when plugged in.


----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  3.  COMPATIBLE USB HARDWARE
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  The riser speaks USB HID - the standard "Human Interface Device" class
  that nearly all plain gamepads, keyboards and mice use.

  WORKS:

    *  USB HID gamepads and joysticks (digital D-pad and/or analog
       sticks; up to 12 buttons can be mapped).
    *  USB HID keyboards.
    *  USB HID mice.
    *  Wireless pads/keyboards/mice that come with their own little USB
       dongle - the dongle is just a HID device to the riser.
    *  Analog sticks: they are read and converted to the eight digital
       joystick directions, so an analog pad works (as a digital one).

  DOES NOT WORK:

    *  USB hubs.  There is no hub support - plug devices straight into
       the two ports, one device per port.
    *  Anything that is not an input device: USB sticks, audio, printers,
       Wi-Fi, etc.  Only keyboards, mice and gamepads are handled.
    *  Bluetooth-only pads with no USB dongle (the riser has no
       Bluetooth radio).

  THE XBOX / XINPUT CATCH (important):

    Xbox 360 / Xbox One style controllers, and pads switched into
    "XInput" / "X" mode, are NOT standard HID - they use Microsoft's
    XInput protocol.  These are unreliable on the riser and are best
    avoided.  The firmware has work-arounds for a few specific adapters,
    but you should not count on an XInput pad working.

    If your pad has a mode switch, use the HID / "DirectInput" / "D" /
    PC mode, NOT the X mode.


----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  4.  CHOOSING A USB GAMEPAD
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  A few things to look for:

    *  HID / DirectInput.  Pick a pad that talks plain USB HID.  Cheap
       "USB joystick" pads, retro-style pads, and many name-brand pads
       in their DirectInput mode all qualify.

    *  Mode switch.  If your pad has a switch for its USB mode, choose
       the HID / DirectInput / "D" / PC mode and avoid XInput / "X".

    *  Tested so far.  Compatibility varies a lot between pads - even
       within one brand - so treat any pad as "try it and see".  Known
       results on this hardware:
         - 8BitDo SFC30, connected by USB CABLE: works.
         - "MR1809WL" wireless pad (dongle), in D-input mode: works.
         - 8BitDo PC Engine (PCE) pad: did NOT work.
         - 8BitDo NeoGeo pad: did NOT work.

    *  A real digital D-pad is ideal.  Amiga games expect digital
       directions, and a crisp D-pad feels best.  Analog-only sticks
       work but are less precise for old digital games.

    *  Enough buttons.  The CD32 layout has seven buttons (Red, Blue,
       Green, Yellow, Play, Rewind, Forward) plus the standard fire.
       A pad with 6 or more face/shoulder buttons lets you map them all.

    *  Bus power.  The pad is powered from the Amiga through the riser.
       Ordinary bus-powered pads and dongles are fine; avoid devices
       that expect a powered hub or draw a lot of current.

  If a pad enumerates but the buttons come out in a strange order, you
  can always map it by hand - and for really odd pads there is a
  raw-discovery tool (see "learn-raw" below).


----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  5.  THE "risergamepad" TOOL
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  "risergamepad" is the Amiga-side utility for checking status and
  mapping your pad's buttons to the Amiga / CD32 functions.  Run it from
  a Shell, or double-click its icon (the icon opens the graphical
  mapper).

  COMMON COMMANDS

    risergamepad                 Show status and the current mapping of
                                 the connected gamepad(s).

    risergamepad learn           Map your pad's buttons, step by step,
                                 from the Shell.

    risergamepad gui             Map your pad using the graphical screen:
                                 a CD32 controller is drawn and a purple
                                 marker ring highlights the button to set;
                                 press the matching button on your pad.

    risergamepad watch           Show live button presses (handy to see
                                 which physical button is which).

  HOW MAPPING WORKS

    For each Amiga / CD32 function the tool asks you to press a button:

      Red (= primary fire) is required - every joystick has at least one
      button.  The rest (Blue, Green, Yellow, Play, Rewind, Forward, and
      the 2nd/3rd fire buttons) are optional; skip any you do not want.

    The mapping is saved automatically and tied to that pad's USB
    identity, so it loads by itself next time (see section 2).

  LESS COMMON COMMANDS

    risergamepad ports           Short one-screen status.
    risergamepad watch-ports     Live status, refreshing.
    risergamepad debug           USB-host diagnostics (for when a device
                                 will not enumerate).
    risergamepad watch-debug     Live diagnostics.
    risergamepad raw             Show raw HID report bytes (developer).
    risergamepad learn-raw       Discover the raw bytes/bits for a pad
                                 that does not auto-detect, then map by
                                 raw bit.
    risergamepad help            Full command list.

  By default "learn" and "watch" work on the joystick-port pad.  Append
  "2" (e.g. "risergamepad learn 2") to target the mouse-port pad instead.

  NOTE: All commands except "help" and "gui demo" need the riser
  hardware present.  If the board is not detected the Shell prints a
  short message and the GUI shows "TF CD32 Riser not detected".  Use
  "risergamepad gui demo" to see the graphical mapper with no hardware.


----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  6.  QUICK START
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

    1.  Plug your USB gamepad into either port on the riser.
    2.  Run  risergamepad        to confirm it is detected.
    3.  Run  risergamepad gui    (or  risergamepad learn ) and follow
        the prompts to map the buttons.
    4.  Done.  The mapping is saved and re-loads whenever you plug that
        pad in.


----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  7.  TROUBLESHOOTING
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

    "TF CD32 Riser not detected"
        The tool cannot see the board.  Check that the riser is fitted
        and seated, and that you are running this on the machine it is
        installed in.

    Pad is plugged in but nothing happens
        Run  risergamepad watch .  If no bits change when you press
        buttons, the pad is probably in XInput mode - switch it to
        DirectInput / "D" / PC mode (see section 3).

    Pad seems dead until you touch it
        Some pads send nothing until the first input.  Press any button
        once to wake it, then try again.

    Buttons are detected but in the wrong order
        Just re-map with  risergamepad learn  or  risergamepad gui .
        For stubborn pads use  risergamepad learn-raw .


----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  8.  TECHNICAL NOTES
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

    *  The riser is memory-mapped on the Amiga bus at $00BA0000.
    *  USB is handled by an STM32F722 HID host with two host ports
       (one high-speed, one full-speed).
    *  Only the USB HID class is implemented (keyboard, mouse, gamepad);
       there is no hub, mass-storage or other class support.
    *  Up to 12 USB buttons plus four directions can be mapped per pad.
    *  Pad profiles are stored in battery-backed registers and keyed by
       USB VID:PID.

